.TH SANDBOX.YAML 5 "2026-05-23" "sudo-logger" "Sudo-logger Configuration"
.SH NAME
sandbox.yaml \- Configuration file for the sudo-logger eBPF LSM process sandbox
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sandbox.yaml
defines a deny-list of files, devices, and processes that are protected against
modification or interference by processes running inside a \fBsudo-logger\fR session.

The restrictions are enforced at the kernel level using \fBeBPF LSM\fR hooks,
making them effective even against the root user within a sandboxed session.
The following hooks are used for enforcement:
.IP \(bu 2
\fBlsm/file_open\fR, \fBlsm/file_permission\fR: Deny write-mode opens on protected inodes.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBlsm/path_truncate\fR, \fBlsm/inode_setattr\fR: Prevent truncation attacks.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBlsm/inode_unlink\fR, \fBlsm/inode_rename\fR: Deny deletion or renaming of protected files.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBlsm/inode_create\fR, \fBlsm/inode_mkdir\fR, \fBlsm/inode_mknod\fR, \fBlsm/inode_symlink\fR: Prevent file creation inside protected directories.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBlsm/task_kill\fR: Prevent sending signals to protected processes.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBlsm/socket_bind\fR: Prevent binding to protected Unix sockets.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBtp_btf/sched_process_fork\fR: Propagate sandbox state to all child processes.
.SH FILE FORMAT
The file uses YAML format with a single top-level \fBprotect\fR key.
.PP
.RS
.nf
\fBprotect:\fR
  \fBfiles:\fR
    \- /etc/sudoers
    \- /etc/sudo-logger
  \fBdevices:\fR
    \- /dev/nvme0n1
  \fBproc:\fR
    \- /proc/sysrq-trigger
  \fBsockets:\fR
    \- /run/sudo-logger/plugin.sock
  \fBprocesses:\fR
    \- auditd
    \- sshd
.fi
.RE
.SH SECTIONS
.TP
.B files
A list of absolute paths to regular files or directories.
Protected files cannot be opened for writing, truncated, deleted, or renamed.
Protected directories cannot have new files or subdirectories created inside them.
Protection is recursive for all existing files found inside a directory at agent startup.
.TP
.B devices
A list of device nodes (e.g., \fB/dev/sda\fR). Prevents raw hardware access.
.TP
.B proc
A list of entries in the \fB/proc\fR filesystem. Prevents modification of sensitive kernel parameters.
.TP
.B sockets
A list of Unix domain socket files. Prevents deletion or replacement of the socket file.
Does \fBnot\fR block \fBconnect(2)\fR or data transmission to the socket.
.TP
.B processes
A list of process names (\fBcomm\fR). Processes in the sandbox are forbidden
from sending \fBany\fR signal (including \fBSIGKILL\fR and \fBSIGTERM\fR)
to these processes.
.IP
This effectively prevents a sandboxed root user from stopping protected systemd
services using \fBsystemctl stop\fR or \fBkill\fR.
.IP
\fBNOTE:\fR Linux process names are limited to 15 characters. Longer names are
truncated. Use \fBcat /proc/<pid>/comm\fR to verify the exact name.
.SH SCOPE
Restrictions only apply to processes that are:
.IP 1.
Members of a \fBsudo-logger\fR session cgroup.
.IP 2.
Descendants of a \fBsudo\fR process tracked by the agent since session start.
.PP
Processes outside of active \fBsudo-logger\fR sessions are completely unaffected.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
Requires \fBCONFIG_BPF_LSM=y\fR and \fBbpf\fR present in the active LSM list
(verify with \fBgrep bpf /sys/kernel/security/lsm\fR).
On Fedora\ 38 and later \fBbpf\fR is active by default; no boot parameter
changes are needed.
On older or non-Fedora kernels add \fBlsm=bpf\fR to \fBGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX\fR
and run \fBgrub2-mkconfig\fR.
.SH FILES
.I /etc/sudo-logger/sandbox.yaml
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sudo-logger-agent (8),
.BR sudo_logger_plugin (8)
